{"title_page": "James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox noble\n|name=The Earl of Lauderdale \n|image=James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale by Thomas Gainsborough.jpg\n|succession=[[Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|reign=17 August 1789 \u2013 10 September 1839\n|predecessor=[[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|successor=[[James Maitland, 9th Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1759|1|26}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|1839|9|10|1759|1|26}}\n|father=[[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|spouse=Eleanor Todd\n|issue=10\n}}\n[[File:James Maitland by Joseph Nollekens, SNPG.JPG|thumb|James Maitland by [[Joseph Nollekens]]]]\n[[File:The Maitland tomb, St Mary's Church, Haddington.jpg|thumb|260px|The Maitland tomb, St Mary's Church, Haddington]]\n'''James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KT|PC}} (26 January 1759 \u2013 10 September 1839) was [[Keeper of the Great Seal of Scotland]] and a [[representative peer]] for [[Scotland]] in the [[House of Lords]].\n\n==Early years==\n\nBorn at [[Haltoun House]] near [[Ratho]], the eldest son and heir of [[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale]], whom he succeeded in 1789, he became a controversial Scottish politician and writer. His tutor had been the learned Dr. [[Andrew Dalzell]] and James Maitland then attended the universities of Edinburgh and Glasgow, completing his education in Paris where, it is said, he became radicalised.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\nUpon his return home in 1780, he was admitted a member of the [[Faculty of Advocates]] and successfully stood for election to parliament the same year. From 1780 until 1784 he was a member of parliament representing [[Newport (Cornwall) (UK Parliament constituency)|Newport]] and from 1784 to 1789, [[Malmesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Malmesbury]]. In the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] he supported the prominent Whig [[Charles James Fox|Charles Fox]] and took an active part in debate and was one of the managers of the [[Impeachment of Warren Hastings]].\n\nFrom 1789, in the [[House of Lords]], where he was a [[representative peer]] for Scotland, he was prominent as an opponent of the policy of [[William Pitt the Younger]] and the English government with regard to France. He was a frequent speaker and also distinguished himself by his active opposition to the ''Habeas Corpus'' Suspension Act, the Sedition Bill, and other measures. Upon the outbreak of the French Revolution, of which he was thought to be in sympathy, he ostentatiously appeared in the house in the rough costume of Jacobinism.\n\nIn July 1792, he fought a bloodless duel with [[Benedict Arnold]] after impugning Arnold's honour in the House of Lords.<ref name=DictCanBio>\n{{cite DCB\n|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/arnold_benedict_5E.html\n|title=Arnold, Benedict\n|volume=5\n|first=Curtis |last=Fahey\n|accessdate=9 December 2007}}\n</ref>\n\n==French Revolution==\nIn 1792, in the company of [[John Moore (Scottish physician)|John Moore]], Lord Lauderdale travelled again to France. The attack on the [[Tuileries]] and the imprisonment of King [[Louis XVI of France]], took place three days after the earl's arrival in the French capital. After the massacres of 2 September, the British ambassador having left Paris, the earl left Paris on the 4th for [[Calais]]. However, he returned to Paris the following month and did not leave for London until 5 December. Upon his return from France/ he published a ''Journal during the residence in France from the beginning of August to the middle of December 1792''.\n\nAccording to [[antiquarian]] Andrew Thomson, \"James Maitland 8th Earl of Lauderdale was known as 'Citizen Maitland'. An extremist, he was in Paris during the [[French Revolution]] and was a personal friend of [[Jean-Paul Marat]]. He rarely visited Scotland.\" The earl had helped to found the British [[Friends of the People Society|Society of the Friends of the People]] in 1792.\n\n==New peerage==\nUpon the formation of the Grenville administration in February 1806, Lauderdale was made a [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peer of the United Kingdom]] as '''Baron Lauderdale of Thirlestane''' and sworn a member of the [[Privy Council]]. For a short time from July 1806 he was keeper of the [[Great Seal of Scotland]].\n\n==Napoleonic treaty==\nOn 2 August 1806 the earl, fully fluent in French, departed for France, invested with full powers to conclude peace, the negotiations for which had been for several weeks carried on by the [[Earl of Yarmouth]]. Arriving on the 5th he and Yarmouth set about the arduous task of treating with [[Napoleon]] and [[Tallyrand]]. Yarmouth was recalled on the 14th and Lauderdale was left alone. Following the renewal of hostilities he left Paris for London on 9 October. A full account of the progress and termination of the negotiations appeared in the ''[[London Gazette]]'' of 21 October 1806.\n\nAfter acting as the leader of the [[British Whig Party|Whigs]] in Scotland, Lauderdale became a [[Tory]] and voted against the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Bill of 1832]]. Lord Lauderdale was made a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in 1806 and a [[Order of the Thistle|Knight of the Thistle]] in 1821.\n\n==Banner dispute==\nIn 1672 on the death of the Earl of Dundee, the Duke of Lauderdale was appointed \nHereditary Bearer for the Sovereign of the Standard of Scotland, and this right was retained by his heirs until 1910.\n\nIn 1790, James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale matriculated arms in the character of Hereditary Bearer for the Sovereign of the Standard of Scotland and Hereditary Bearer for the Sovereign of the National Flag of Scotland.\n\nIn 1852 after a meeting with the Earls of Lauderdale and Dundee the [[Lord Lyon]] advised the Queen to confirm the Earl of Lauderdale's right to bear the [[Flag of Scotland|saltire]] as [[the Bearer of the National Flag of Scotland]], and to confirm that the [[Earl of Dundee]] as [[the Bearer of the Royal Banner]] bears the [[Royal Standard of the United Kingdom|Royal Standard]] of the lion rampant.\n\n==Writings==\n[[File:Lauderdale - Inquiry into the nature and origin of public wealth, and into the means and causes of its increase, 1819 - 5224440.tif|thumb|''Inquiry into the nature and origin of public wealth'', 1819]]\n\nMaitland wrote an ''Inquiry into the Nature and Origin of Public Wealth'' (1804 and 1819), in which he introduced the concept that has come to be known as the \"Lauderdale Paradox\": there is an inverse correlation between public wealth and private wealth; an increase in the one can only come at the cost of a decrease in the other.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n  |first1=Brett|last1=Clark\n  |first2=John Bellamy|last2=Foster\n  |title=Marx's Ecology in the 21st Century\n  |journal=World Review of Political Economy\n  |volume=1\n  |number=1\n  |page=142\n  |year=2010\n  |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/517fe876e4b03c6b86a4b81b/t/550fc115e4b07d4393b1c671/1427095829285/Marx+and+the+laurderdale+Paradox.pdf\n}}</ref>  This work, which was translated into French and Italian, produced a controversy between the author and [[Henry Peter Brougham, 1st Baron Brougham and Vaux|Lord Brougham]]; ''The Depreciation of the Paper-currency of Great Britain Proved'' (1812); and other writings of a similar nature.\nThe \"Inquiry\" was the first work to draw attention to the economic consequences of a budget surplus or deficit and its influence on the expansion or contraction of the economy, and was thus the basis of the later Keynesian economic theories which are now widely applied.\n\n==Death==\nHe died at [[Thirlestane Castle]], near [[Lauder]], Berwickshire, at 80.\n\nHe is buried in the Maitland vault, also called the Lauderdale Aisle, at [[St Mary's Collegiate Church, Haddington]].\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Kauffmann, Angelica - Portrait of Eleanor, Countess of Lauderdale - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Eleanor Todd, Countess of Lauderdale, painted by [[Angelica Kauffman|Angelica Kauffmann]] ]]\nHe married on 15 August 1782, Eleanor Todd (1762\u20131856), only daughter and heiress of Anthony Todd, Secretary of the [[General Post Office]]. They had ten children : \n* Lady Eleanor, married [[James Balfour (died 1845)|James Balfour]] (parents of [[James Maitland Balfour]] MP, and grandparents of Prime Minister [[Arthur Balfour]])\n* Lady Mary, married Edward Stanley of Cross Hall, near Ormskirk. Mother of [[Edward Stanley (Bridgwater MP)|Edward Stanley MP]].\n* Lady Julia, married in 1823 [[Baron Bruntisfield|Sir John Warrender, 5th Baronet]] (1786\u20131867)\n* [[James Maitland, 9th Earl of Lauderdale]] (1784\u20131860)\n* Admiral Sir Anthony Maitland, 10th Earl of Lauderdale (1785\u20131863)\n* Five other sons.\nNone of his seven sons were married.\n\n== Works ==\n* [http://socserv2.mcmaster.ca/~econ/ugcm/3ll3/lauderdale/InquiryNatureOriginPublicWealth.pdf An Inquiry into The Nature and Origin of Public Wealth and into the Means and Causes of its Increase] 1804 (second edition 1819)\n\n==References==\n* Anderson, William, ''The Scottish Nation'', Edinburgh, 1867, vol.i, p.&nbsp;637\u2013638.\n* ''Lauder & Lauderdale'', by Andrew Thomson, FSA (Scot), [[Galashiels]], 1902.\n* {{cite DNB |wstitle=Maitland, James |volume=35 |first=George Fisher Russell |last=Barker |pp=355-357}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-maitland-1 | the Earl of Lauderdale }}\n* [http://repository.tku.ac.jp/dspace/handle/11150/985/ Book Collection]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Sir John Frederick, 5th Baronet|John Frederick]] <br/> [[Richard Bull (MP)|Richard Bull]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = Member of Parliament for [[Newport (Cornwall) (UK Parliament constituency)|Newport]]\n       | with   = [[Sir John Coghill, 1st Baronet of Richings|John Coghill]]\n       | years  = [[1780 British general election|1780]] \u2013 [[1784 British general election|1784]] }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Sir John Coghill, 1st Baronet of Richings|Sir John Coghill, Bt]] <br/> [[Sir John Riggs-Miller, 1st Baronet|Sir John Riggs-Miller, Bt]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[John Calvert (died 1844)|John Calvert]] <br/> [[Arthur Hill, 2nd Marquess of Downshire|Viscount Fairford]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = Member of Parliament for [[Malmesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Malmesbury]]\n       | with   = [[Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne|The Viscount Melbourne]]\n       | years  = [[1784 British general election|1784]]\u20131789 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne|The Viscount Melbourne]] <br/> [[Paul Benfield]] }}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Alexander Gordon, 4th Duke of Gordon|Alexander Gordon]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Keeper of the Great Seal of Scotland]]\n       | years  = 1806\u20131807 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Alexander Gordon, 4th Duke of Gordon|Alexander Gordon]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale|James Maitland]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Lauderdale]]\n       | years  = 1789\u20131839 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[James Maitland, 9th Earl of Lauderdale|James Maitland]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|gb}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Baron Lauderdale of Thirlestane]]\n       | years  = 1806\u20131839 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[James Maitland, 9th Earl of Lauderdale|James Maitland]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Classical economists}}\n{{History of economic thought}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauderdale, James Maitland, 8th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1759 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Keepers of the Great Seal of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish representative peers]]\n[[Category:Earls of Lauderdale]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Thistle|Maitland, James]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies|Maitland, James]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Maitland, James]]\n[[Category:Members of the Faculty of Advocates]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United Kingdom to France]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:Classical economists]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox noble\n|name=The Earl of Lauderdale \n|image=James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale by Thomas Gainsborough.jpg\n|succession=[[Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|reign=17 August 1789 \u2013 10 September 1839\n|predecessor=[[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|successor=[[James Maitland, 9th Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1759|1|26}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|1839|9|10|1759|1|26}}\n|father=[[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale]]\n|spouse=Eleanor Todd\n|issue=10\n}}\n[[File:James Maitland by Joseph Nollekens, SNPG.JPG|thumb|James Maitland by [[Joseph Nollekens]]]]\n[[File:The Maitland tomb, St Mary's Church, Haddington.jpg|thumb|260px|The Maitland tomb, St Mary's Church, Haddington]]\n'''James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KT|PC}} (26 January 1759 \u2013 10 September 1839) was [[Keeper of the Great Seal of Scotland]] and a [[representative peer]] for [[Scotland]] in the [[House of Lords]].\n\n==Early years==\n\nBorn at [[Haltoun House]] near [[Ratho]], the eldest son and heir of [[James Maitland, 7th Earl of Lauderdale]], whom he succeeded in 1789, he became a controversial Scottish politician and writer. His tutor had been the learned Dr. [[Andrew Dalzell]] and James Maitland then attended the universities of Edinburgh and Glasgow, completing his education in Paris where, it is said, he became radicalised.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\nUpon his return home in 1780, he was admitted a member of the [[Faculty of Advocates]] and successfully stood for election to parliament the same year. From 1780 until 1784 he was a member of parliament representing [[Newport (Cornwall) (UK Parliament constituency)|Newport]] and from 1784 to 1789, [[Malmesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Malmesbury]]. In the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] he supported the prominent Whig [[Charles James Fox|Charles Fox]] and took an active part in debate and was one of the managers of the [[Impeachment of Warren Hastings]].\n\nFrom 1789, in the [[House of Lords]], where he was a [[representative peer]] for Scotland, he was prominent as an opponent of the policy of [[William Pitt the Younger]] and the English government with regard to France. He was a frequent speaker and also distinguished himself by his active opposition to the ''Habeas Corpus'' Suspension Act, the Sedition Bill, and other measures. Upon the outbreak of the French Revolution, of which he was thought to be in sympathy, he ostentatiously appeared in the house in the rough costume of Jacobinism.\n\nIn July 1792, he fought a bloodless duel with [[Benedict Arnold]] after impugning Arnold's honour in the House of Lords.<ref name=DictCanBio>\n{{cite DCB\n|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/arnold_benedict_5E.html\n|title=Arnold, Benedict\n|volume=5\n|first=Curtis |last=Fahey\n|accessdate=9 December 2007}}\n</ref>\n\n==French Revolution==\nIn 1792, in the company of [[John Moore (Scottish physician)|John Moore]], Lord Lauderdale travelled again to France. The attack on the [[Tuileries]] and the imprisonment of King [[Louis XVI of France]], took place three days after the earl's arrival in the French capital. After the massacres of 2 September, the British ambassador having left Paris, the earl left Paris on the 4th for [[Calais]]. However, he returned to Paris the following month and did not leave for London until 5 December. Upon his return from France/ he published a ''Journal during the residence in France from the beginning of August to the middle of December 1792''.\n\nAccording to [[antiquarian]] Andrew Thomson, \"James Maitland 8th Earl of Lauderdale was known as 'Citizen Maitland'. An extremist, he was in Paris during the [[French Revolution]] and was a personal friend of [[Jean-Paul Marat]]. He rarely visited Scotland.\" The earl had helped to found the British [[Friends of the People Society|Society of the Friends of the People]] in 1792.\n\n==New peerage==\nUpon the formation of the Grenville administration in February 1806, Lauderdale was made a [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peer of the United Kingdom]] as '''Baron Lauderdale of Thirlestane''' and sworn a member of the [[Privy Council]]. For a short time from July 1806 he was keeper of the [[Great Seal of Scotland]].\n\n==Napoleonic treaty==\nOn 2 August 1806 the earl, fully fluent in French, departed for France, invested with full powers to conclude peace, the negotiations for which had been for several weeks carried on by the [[Earl of Yarmouth]]. Arriving on the 5th he and Yarmouth set about the arduous task of treating with [[Napoleon]] and [[Tallyrand]]. Yarmouth was recalled on the 14th and Lauderdale was left alone. Following the renewal of hostilities he left Paris for London on 9 October. A full account of the progress and termination of the negotiations appeared in the ''[[London Gazette]]'' of 21 October 1806.\n\nAfter acting as the leader of the [[British Whig Party|Whigs]] in Scotland, Lauderdale became a [[Tory]] and voted against the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Bill of 1832]]. Lord Lauderdale was made a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in 1806 and a [[Order of the Thistle|Knight of the Thistle]] in 1821.\n\n==Banner dispute==\nIn 1672 on the death of the Earl of Dundee, the Duke of Lauderdale was appointed \nHereditary Bearer for the Sovereign of the Standard of Scotland, and this right was retained by his heirs until 1910.\n\nIn 1790, James Maitland, 8th Earl of Lauderdale matriculated arms in the character of Hereditary Bearer for the Sovereign of the Standard of Scotland and Hereditary Bearer for the Sovereign of the National Flag of Scotland.\n\nIn 1852 after a meeting with the Earls of Lauderdale and Dundee the [[Lord Lyon]] advised the Queen to confirm the Earl of Lauderdale's right to bear the [[Flag of Scotland|saltire]] as [[the Bearer of the National Flag of Scotland]], and to confirm that the [[Earl of Dundee]] as [[the Bearer of the Royal Banner]] bears the [[Royal Standard of the United Kingdom|Royal Standard]] of the lion rampant.\n\n==Writings==\n[[File:Lauderdale - Inquiry into the nature and origin of public wealth, and into the means and causes of its increase, 1819 - 5224440.tif|thumb|''Inquiry into the nature and origin of public wealth'', 1819]]\n\nMaitland wrote an ''Inquiry into the Nature and Origin of Public Wealth'' (1804 and 1819), in which he introduced the concept that has come to be known as the \"Lauderdale Paradox\": there is an inverse correlation between public wealth and private wealth; an increase in the one can only come at the cost of a decrease in the other.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n  |first1=Brett|last1=Clark\n  |first2=John Bellamy|last2=Foster\n  |title=Marx's Ecology in the 21st Century\n  |journal=World Review of Political Economy\n  |volume=1\n  |number=1\n  |page=142\n  |year=2010\n  |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/517fe876e4b03c6b86a4b81b/t/550fc115e4b07d4393b1c671/1427095829285/Marx+and+the+laurderdale+Paradox.pdf\n}}</ref>  This work, which was translated into French and Italian, produced a controversy between the author and [[Henry Peter Brougham, 1st Baron Brougham and Vaux|Lord Brougham]]; ''The Depreciation of the Paper-currency of Great Britain Proved'' (1812); and other writings of a similar nature.\nThe \"Inquiry\" was the first work to draw attention to the economic consequences of a budget surplus or deficit and its influence on the expansion or contraction of the economy, and was thus the basis of the later Keynesian economic theories which are now widely applied.\n\n==Death==\nHe died at [[Thirlestane Castle]], near [[Lauder]], Berwickshire, at 80.\n\nHe is buried in the Maitland vault, also called the Lauderdale Aisle, at [[St Mary's Collegiate Church, Haddington]].\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Kauffmann, Angelica - Portrait of Eleanor, Countess of Lauderdale - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Eleanor Todd, Countess of Lauderdale, painted by [[Angelica Kauffman|Angelica Kauffmann]] ]]\nHe married on 15 August 1782, Eleanor Todd (1762\u20131856), only daughter and heiress of Anthony Todd, Secretary of the [[General Post Office]]. They had ten children : \n* Lady Eleanor, married [[James Balfour (died 1845)|James Balfour]] (parents of [[James Maitland Balfour]] MP, and grandparents of Prime Minister [[Arthur Balfour]])\n* Lady Mary, married Edward Stanley of Cross Hall, near Ormskirk. Mother of [[Edward Stanley (Bridgwater MP)|Edward Stanley MP]].\n* Lady Julia, married in 1823 [[Baron Bruntisfield|Sir John Warrender, 5th Baronet]] (1786\u20131867)\n* [[James Maitland, 9th Earl of Lauderdale]] (1784\u20131860)\n* Admiral Sir Anthony Maitland, 10th Earl of Lauderdale (1785\u20131863)\n* Five other sons.\nNone of his seven sons were married.\n\n== Works ==\n* [http://socserv2.mcmaster.ca/~econ/ugcm/3ll3/lauderdale/InquiryNatureOriginPublicWealth.pdf An Inquiry into The Nature and Origin of Public Wealth and into the Means and Causes of its Increase] 1804 (second edition 1819)\n\n==References==\n* Anderson, William, ''The Scottish Nation'', Edinburgh, 1867, vol.i, p.&nbsp;637\u2013638.\n* ''Lauder & Lauderdale'', by Andrew Thomson, FSA (Scot), [[Galashiels]], 1902.\n* {{cite DNB |wstitle=Maitland, James |volume=35 |first=George Fisher Russell |last=Barker |pp=355-357}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-maitland-1 | the Earl of Lauderdale }}\n* [http://repository.tku.ac